3888723088																										130125215										http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/			2022-08-10T00:57:21Z			https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/130125215					M. Whitson												iNaturalist	Observations	iNaturalist research-grade observations		HumanObservation				https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/130125215	130125215		M. Whitson					male	adult																Emerald Ash Borers moved through our area, and within about two years, most of the ash trees were gone from our woods. There was a huge ash (green or white) at the head of the trail at the Campbell County Environmental Education Center, and I paused to mourn its passing. Then I saw the flickers of green as the emerging ash borers flew up from the remnants. Note that about 6 feet of the trunk was left in place. If you must cut a tree, leaving a bit of the trunk (as much as possible, but short enough not to be a falling hazard) is a great way to support your local wildlife. It's still useful to insects, fungi, woodpeckers, and critters in want of a perch.											2014-06-17T14:01:00-04:00	14:01:00-04:00						2014/06/17 2:01 PM																US	Kentucky				Campbell County Environmental Education Center, Campbell County, KY, USA												38.8926444398	-84.3741731871	EPSG:4326																																			287062292				M.
